#import "../../book.typ": *
// ===================== ANA B’KOACH =====================
// Verse structure (Daniel, 2026-07-08): the seven-line acrostic is set as
// paired verses — lines 1+2, 3+4, 5+6 — with line 7 folded into the whispered
// "Baruch shem" coda as the closing verse. Pairing also compacts the unit onto
// one folio, which pulls L'cha Dodi's Hebrew onto a single open spread.
#startprayer("Ana B’koach", "אָנָּא בְּכֹחַ")
#stanza("Ana b’koach g’dulat y’mincha tatir tz’rura. Kabel rinat amcha, sagvenu, taharenu, nora.",
  "אָנָּא בְּכֹחַ גְּדֻלַּת יְמִינְךָ תַּתִּיר צְרוּרָה. קַבֵּל רִנַּת עַמְּךָ שַׂגְּבֵנוּ טַהֲרֵנוּ נוֹרָא.")
#stanza("Na gibor, dorshei yichudcha k’vavat shomrem. Barchem, taharem, rachamem, tzidkatcha tamid gomlem.",
  "נָא גִבּוֹר דּוֹרְשֵׁי יִחוּדְךָ כְּבָבַת שָׁמְרֵם. בָּרְכֵם טַהֲרֵם רַחֲמֵם צִדְקָתְךָ תָּמִיד גָּמְלֵם.")
#stanza("Chasin kadosh, b’rov tuvcha nahel adatecha. Yachid ge’e, l’amcha p’ne, zochrei k’dushatecha.",
  "חֲסִין קָדוֹשׁ בְּרֹב טוּבְךָ נַהֵל עֲדָתֶךָ. יָחִיד גֵּאֶה לְעַמְּךָ פְּנֵה, זוֹכְרֵי קְדֻשָּׁתֶךָ.")
#rubric([Baruch shem is said softly, as after the Sh’ma])
#stanza("Shav’atenu kabel ushma tza’akatenu, yode’a ta’alumot. Baruch shem k’vod malchuto l’olam va’ed.",
  "שַׁוְעָתֵנוּ קַבֵּל וּשְׁמַע צַעֲקָתֵנוּ יוֹדֵעַ תַּעֲלוּמוֹת. בָּרוּךְ שֵׁם כְּבוֹד מַלְכוּתוֹ לְעוֹלָם וָעֶד.")
#eng("Please — by the great strength of Your right hand, set the bound ones free. Receive the glad song of Your people; lift us, purify us, awesome One.")
#eng("Please, Mighty One — guard those who seek Your oneness like the pupil of an eye. Bless them, purify them, show them compassion; let Your justice always be their reward.")
#eng("Mighty and holy One, in Your abundant goodness, guide Your community. You who are one and exalted, turn toward Your people — those who call Your holiness to mind.")
#engn("Accept our cry and hear our plea, You who know all that is hidden. Blessed is the name of Your glorious majesty forever and ever.",
  [Seven lines of six words each hide, in their opening letters, the mystical forty-two-letter Name
  of God — a prayer folded quietly inside a prayer. Tradition assigns it to the first-century sage
  Nechunya ben HaKanah, but scholars read that as legend and the poem itself as most likely medieval;
  the reaching-out is no less real for that.])
